04440nam a22006015i 9780823295029DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20221992nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232950297 a10.1515/97808232950292doi  a(DE-B1597)575229  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360302bisacsh1 aCrane, Elaine F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Dependent People :bNewport, Rhode Island in the Revolutionary Era /cElaine F. Crane. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (196 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tDescription of the Town of Newport, Rhode Island -- tABBREVIATIONS AND SHORT TITLES -- tCONTENTS -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tIntroduction -- tI "A Good Voyage and Safe Return" -- t1. "Any Scheme of Trade" -- t2. "The First Wheel of Commerce" -- tReflections -- tII An Interdependent People -- t3. A Mercantile Metropolis -- t4. The World of the Wealthy -- t5. Dependent People, Helping Hands -- t6. The Cruel Sea -- t7. The Black Community -- t8. A Lawless Rabble -- tReflections -- tIII A Dependent People -- t9. Economic Arguments and Mob Rule -- t10. A Town at War with Itself -- tReflections -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis work tells a story about the sea, an American colonial town, and the British. It relates how Newport's dependence on the Atlantic Ocean dominated nearly every aspect of its existence. Newport learned early from its watery surroundings that its survival and prosperity were inextricably linked to commerce. Dependent on a thriving trade, Newporters were willing to explore and combination of routes which suggested a successful return in voyage and investment. Newport's single-minded commitment to commerce produced a society in which people were also dependent on each other. Merchant and dockworker, sailmaker and rope-walk owner developed symbiotic relationships as a result of their common efforts to ensure the success of each voyage. Dependency also extended to social networks where the affluent took responsibility for other members of the community. Because of their dependence on unobstructed trade, Newporters had evaded British customs for generations, using methods which cast some doubt on their commitment to the law. Thus, when it became clear in 1764 that Britain would go to great lengths to enforce new duties, the stage was set for confrontation. In the end, events outstripped the ability of Newport to chart its own course as the violence escalated. The Revolution prematurely ended Newport's golden age and destroyed the town both physically and spiritually. A dependent people had gained independence but at a cost only a few could foresee.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh1 aMaylem, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311074329640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295029/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK